Surviving session loss.

Here is a trap that catches everyone eventually. When you log out, or your s-s-h connection drops, the shell sends a hangup signal to all of its jobs. Most programs treat that signal as a polite instruction to exit, which means closing your terminal also kills the background jobs you left running. For anything long-running, you need a way around that.

The simplest is no-hup, spelled n-o-h-u-p. It runs a command with the hangup signal ignored, and tidily redirects its output to a file called no-hup dot out. The command then keeps running even after the shell that started it is gone. A close cousin is disown, which removes a job from the shell's job table altogether, so the shell forgets about it and will not send it the hangup signal on exit; it is handy for rescuing a job you have already started in the background. And set-s-i-d goes further, launching a command in a brand-new session with no controlling terminal at all, the cleanest way to fully detach something.

But the modern, better answer is a terminal multiplexer, either t-mux or screen. Instead of detaching individual commands, you run the multiplexer as a long-lived session that hosts your shells inside it. Your s-s-h connection can die, the multiplexer keeps running on the server, and when you reconnect you simply attach back to your session and find everything exactly as you left it. With t-mux you start a session, do your work, press a key combination to detach, and later reattach. For most serious work this is the right tool; no-hup and disown remain useful for quick one-offs, but a multiplexer solves the whole problem far more gracefully.
